2. Question:¶

An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions.

We surmise from the data provided and question posed that a random sample of 10 was taken, the failure rate provided is equal across trials, only a success or failure is possible and the trials are independent (As in result of one event does not influence others) . Hence we can safely assume that the distibution will follow a binomial distribution.¶
So to answer this question first let us visualise and create the required binomial distribution¶
In [5]:

3. Question:¶

A car salesman sells on an average 3 cars per week.

A. Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars. B. Probability that in a given week he will sell 2 or more but less than 5 cars. C. Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold perweek.

We surmise from the data provided and question posed that there is no upper limit of cars sold, we have been provided the rate by the question which is a constant and we can assume that the event of selling each car are independent events. Hence we assume that the function follows a poisson distribution.¶
So to answer this question first let us visualise and create the required possion distribution¶
In [12]:
#average rate of car sold per week, denoted with lambda in the question for poisson distribution 

rate = 3

#a numpy array of different no. of successes ranging from 0 to 19 to construct a probability distribution

n=np.arange(0,20)

#calculating the distribution and storing the distribution of probablitites in an array
poisson = stats.poisson.pmf(n,rate)

#printing the probability distribution for different values of x
poisson

C. Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold perweek.¶

To plot the cumulative distribution we must understand how it is different from the chart at the start of the answer. Cumulative probability means the sum of all the values present on the left of the x-axis point. This can be easily constructed through a loop which add all the values which appear on the left in the poisson list.¶
In [16]:
# Initialising the new list
poisson_cdf = [None]*len(poisson)

# Creating the new variable with cumulative probability distribution
for idx in range(len(poisson)):
    poisson_cdf[idx] = sum(poisson[:idx])
In [17]:
# Plotting the poisson cumulative probability distribution 

plt.plot(n,poisson_cdf,'o-')
plt.title('Poisson: $\lambda$ = %i ' % rate)
plt.xlabel('Cars sold in a week')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Probability of Number of Cars \nsold in a week')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

# Removing Variables

# Visualising a normal distribution with mean 60 and sigma 12
mu, sigma = 60, 12
s = np.random.normal(mu, sigma, 300)

# Create the bins and histogram
count, bins, ignored = plt.hist(s, 10, histtype='step')

# Plot the distribution curve
plt.plot(bins, 1/(sigma * np.sqrt(2 * np.pi)) *
    np.exp( - (bins - mu)**2 / (2 * sigma**2) ), linewidth=3, color='y')
plt.show()

# Randomising the process of creating a normal distribution of this example a thousand times
mu, sigma = 60, 12
# Storing the sum of all the percentage values for marks greater than 80
err = 0

for n in range(1000):
    s = np.random.normal(mu, sigma, 300)
    err = err + (len(s[s>80])/300)

# Finding the mean over 1000 repetitions
err/1000

# Creating the mean, standard deviation and answer variables
mean = 60
sd = 12
ans = 1 - stats.norm.cdf(80, loc=mean, scale=sd)

# Printing the answer
print("The percentage of students who score more than 80 is %2.4f%%" %(ans*100))

# Loading the dataset in df_bb with '-' as Null values
df_bb = pd.read_csv("DS - Part2 - Basketball.csv", na_values='-')

# Converting TeamLaunch into more meaningful format. Wherever TeamLaunch is more than 1 year we keep the last date as the year.
# Initialising a list to collect all the new values
TeamLaunch_list = []

# Looping through TeamLaunch and extracting the meaningful format
for val in df_bb["TeamLaunch"]:
    TeamLaunch_list.append(val[:2]+val[-2:])
    
# Assigning the new list to the column TeamLaunch
df_bb["TeamLaunch"] = TeamLaunch_list

# Converting the column TeamLaunch to year
df_bb["TeamLaunch"] = pd.to_datetime(df_bb["TeamLaunch"]).dt.year

# Converting Null Float to 0
df_bb.iloc[:, 2:11] = df_bb.iloc[:, 2:11].fillna(0)

# Converting float columns to integer datatype
df_bb = df_bb.astype({"Score": 'int', "PlayedGames":'int', "WonGames":'int', "DrawnGames":'int', "LostGames":'int',

Now let us create some new features for analysis¶

The limitation of the previous features are apparent. Which is that most teams cannot be compared with each other with the available information. So we will create new stats and features to achieve the same. We will apply these stats to a copy so as to not affect the original.¶
In [40]:
# Creating a copy
df_bb_stats = df_bb.copy()
In [41]:
# New stat Win Ratio which is wins per game
df_bb_stats["Win_Ratio"] = df_bb_stats["WonGames"]/df_bb_stats["PlayedGames"]

# New stat Loss Ratio which is loss per game
df_bb_stats["Loss_Ratio"] = df_bb_stats["LostGames"]/df_bb_stats["PlayedGames"]

# New stat Draw Ratio which is draws per game
df_bb_stats["Draw_Ratio"] = df_bb_stats["DrawnGames"]/df_bb_stats["PlayedGames"]

# New stat Basket Given Ratio which is Basket Given per game
df_bb_stats["BasketGiven_Ratio"] = df_bb_stats["BasketGiven"]/df_bb_stats["PlayedGames"]

# New stat Basket Scored Ratio which is Basket Scored per game
df_bb_stats["BasketScored_Ratio"] = df_bb_stats["BasketScored"]/df_bb_stats["PlayedGames"]

# New stat Score to Basket which is average points recieved per basket (This is useful as basket points range from 1 to 4)
df_bb_stats["Score2Basket"] = df_bb_stats["Score"]/df_bb_stats["BasketScored"]

# New stat Games to Tournament which is games played per tournament (This is useful since more a team plays er tournament more exposure they get)
df_bb_stats["Games2Tournament"] = df_bb_stats["PlayedGames"]/df_bb_stats["Tournament"]

# New stat Tournament years, this is the number years from inception to current year and hence the number of available years to play in the tournament
df_bb_stats["Tournyears"] = 2018 - df_bb_stats["TeamLaunch"]

From Inference 6 we will not classify Win and Loss Ratio but instead mark only the teams with a positive Win to Loss Ratio as Good. No further classification of good will be done is good itself is only 13% of the data.¶

df_bb_stats["Engagement"] = df_bb_stats["Draw_Ratio"].apply(lambda x: "Boring" if x >= median else "Not_Boring")

3. Please include any improvements or suggestions to the association management on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected by the association to perform a better data analysis in future¶

The data could be masked data and not the entire data. This seems to be true since in many cases the Total Score is less than the number of baskets scored, and Games Played compared to Score, Basket Scored, Basket Given etc seems to be quite low as well.¶
Traditionally a Basketball game could have 1, 2, 3 or even 4 (rarely) points per basket. An analysis where we could determine how a team scores its points (How many 3 pointers) would give a wealth of knowledge on the team itself. This was not possible in this dataset and elements which would help us analyse the team playing style more would be very helpful.¶
To sum up more data and more complete data would have greatly improved this dataset. Also more information on clients motivations to sponsor teams which play in a tournament organised by the client itself (despite the conflict of interest) would help us understand what to recommend.¶

null_list = ["-", " ", "  "]

# Looping through all columns available
for idx in range(len(df_stup.columns)):
    # Printing useful information
    print("Column Name : ", df_stup.columns[idx])
    print("Verdict")
    flag = 0
    
    # Looping through all values in null_list
    for elem in null_list:
        # Comparing each value of null_list all unique values of a column
        if elem in df_stup[df_stup.columns[idx]].unique():
            
            # Printing the the null value signal found and encouraging manual detection
            print("Null Found:", elem, " Manually check Values")
            print(df_stup[df_stup.columns[idx]].unique())
            flag = 1
            break
    
    # Printing helpful information when null values are not found
    if flag == 0:
        print("No null values")
    
    # For cosmetic purposes inserting blank line
    print("\n")

In [62]:
# Initialising a list which will be used to make necessary calculation for the new 'Funding' feature
Funding_list = []

# Looping through each value of Funding column to extract necessary information
for val in df_stup["Funding"]:
    
    # Checking if last string is K(thousand), M(million) & B(billion)
    if val[-1] == 'K':
        # Trimming each value of this condition to get float value and then multiplying by 1000(K) to get the required integer
        Funding_list.append(int(float(val[1:-1])*1000))
    elif val[-1] == 'M':
        # Trimming each value of this condition to get float value and then multiplying by 100K(M) to get the required integer
        Funding_list.append(int(float(val[1:-1])*1000000))
    elif val[-1] == 'B':
        # Trimming each value of this condition to get float value and then multiplying by 100M(B) to get the required integer
        Funding_list.append(int(float(val[1:-1])*1000000000))

• Calculate percentage of winners that are still operating and percentage of contestants that are still operating¶
In [75]:
# Calculating the proportion size based on winner and contestant (Denominator)
winner_size = len(df_stup[df_stup["Result"] == "Winner"])
contestant_size = len(df_stup[df_stup["Result"] == "Contestant"])

# Calculating the size of the required event of Operating while winner or contestant (Numerator)
winner2operating_size = len(df_stup[(df_stup["Result"] == "Winner") & (df_stup["OperatingState"] == "Operating")])
contestant2operating_size = len(df_stup[(df_stup["Result"] == "Contestant") & (df_stup["OperatingState"] == "Operating")])

# Calculating the proportion of Operating winner and Operating contestant (Numerator)
pct_win2oprt = (winner2operating_size/winner_size)
pct_cont2oprt = (contestant2operating_size/contestant_size)

# Displaying the Percentages calculated for the question
print("Percentage of winners that are still operating is %2.4f%%\nPercentage of contestants that are still operating is %2.4f%%" %(pct_win2oprt*100, pct_cont2oprt*100))

• Write your hypothesis comparing the proportion of companies that are operating between winners and contestants:¶
 Write the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis.
 Test for significance and conclusion
Ho is proportion(operating&winne/winner) - proportion(operating&contestant/contestant) = 0¶
Ha is proportion(operating&winne/winner) - proportion(operating&contestant/contestant) ≠ 0¶
Testing our Null Hypothesis against a 90% significance¶
In [76]:
# Calculating the confidence interval at 90% Significance ising proportions calculated earlier
# Calculating standard error
std_err = math.sqrt(((pct_win2oprt*(1-pct_win2oprt))/24)+((pct_cont2oprt*(1-pct_cont2oprt))/311))

# Calculating the range of 90% significance 
upper_bound = (pct_win2oprt - pct_cont2oprt)+(1.96*std_err)
lower_bound = (pct_win2oprt - pct_cont2oprt)-(1.96*std_err)

# Printing useful information and suggestions
print("Lower Bound around proportion difference ", lower_bound)
print("Upper Bound around proportion difference ", upper_bound, "\n")

if (lower_bound < 0) & (upper_bound > 0):
    print("Since zero lies within 90% signifance of the measured difference hence we accept the Null Hypothesis")
else:
    print("Since zero does not lie within 90% signifance of the measured difference hence we can reject the Null Hypothesis")

Lower Bound around proportion difference  -0.16559164790216785
Upper Bound around proportion difference  0.2124833949546866 

Since zero lies within 90% signifance of the measured difference hence we accept the Null Hypothesis
Based on above advice we should not reject the Null Hypothesis,¶
proportion(operating&winne/winner) - proportion(operating&contestant/contestant) = 0;¶
which can be read as proportion(operating&winne/winner) = proportion(operating&contestant/contestant)¶
Thus our conclusion is that the proportion of Operating winners and proportion of Operating Contestants are quite similar. Which might suggest that the Winning or being a Contestant does not play much of a role in a Company being Operational.¶
